uFaod.content:
It was supposed to be an space 
- opera in 3D animation
that explains how to connect to our network

We used a respectable 
animation software, 
but results were terrible

So we decided to ditch it
-
it was too low-key even 
for our lo-fi taste.

Which is really a pity,
because the idea was great.

It features Barbara as the only inhabitant of a comet travelling through space, 
eating pizza and contemplating storytelling

She encounters various characters and objects from many different stories, 
all floating around her, like space debris
Here are some good stills, just to give you an idea:

apAZt.content:
While you connect to wifi,
Barbara is counting the stars
Than there is a cosmic storm during which she screams about how exciting it is to find herself in a place not covered by Google maps

MhC3H.content:
After the storm calms down,
she tells you to open your Chrome / Safari / Firefox etc,
and enter : futur.pizza
in your address bar.

uFaod.content: This peaceful moment is than brutally interrupted
Because the asteroid is suddenly torched by a passing dragon
and everything dissolves into white nothingness

MhC3H.content:
Address bar - NOT search bar! 
And while youre trying to figure out the difference between the two, 
she practices her ukulele

E1DFV.content:
I am a hero in a play. 
It's a kind of lo-fi space-opera, in which I fight against my own monsters using a bombastic red keyboard hung around the neck like in the heyday of 80s synth-pop.
How does it end?
Theatre directors want their play to end with a gripping monologue, like that of Charlie Chaplin at the end of The Great Dictator. How could this monologue begin?

Im not afraid of the dark any more.
Things like this happen all the time.
I also have a fear of not having water.
So, as a precaution, I put in aluminium, but I'm not sure it really helps
Then other characters came on stage, and there was a lot of interaction and interaction. But it was too complicated.
So a machine by the name James Joyce wrote a play called Ulysses.
It was a little better.
The end.
Theatre directors want their play to end with an epic song, in magic realism style. How to make this happen?

An asteroid hits the stage, absorbing everything into a black hole.  Spectators stay glued to their seats for days, watching the hole waiting for something to happen. It is a wonderful visual spectacle. But the end is not the only end.
Spectators organise into a union. One of them sings: Let's all get on stage and have a good old time
